This definition of Logic as an Art arose from the dialec- tical and rhetorical innovations introduced hythe reformers of Logic in the latter part of the fifteenth century, and was adopted universally by Ramus and his followers, as well as by the Peripatetico-Ramists of the school of Keckermann, and afterwards by the Cartesians. Among the earlier philo- sophers, the Peripatetics considered Logic to be neither Art nor Science, but an Instrument. The Stoics regarded it as a Science, in which they were followed by the Schoolmen.
